Actually the correct annotation would be:

/**
 * @type {function}
 */
var callback;

JSDoc type expressions are enclosed in braces.

Hmm I mistyped mine as well. All of the following work:

/** @type {function()} */
/** @type function() */

However with or without braces, "function" does require the parens.

Looks like you were right the first time as well:  /** @type {function} */ does not emit a warning.  But as mentioned above, jsdoc will not generate proper documentation if the @type annotation contains braces.  It's only important when the type is itself a type that jsdoc has seen, e.g., a class that is defined elsewhere in your javascript.  But it is important for us to be able to link between non-native types within our JSDoc documentation, and therefore including the braces is not an option for us (until JSDoc supports braces in @type annotations).

Either way, I still think the error could be made less cryptic, such as what is reported in @param (since in @param, even JSDoc requires the braces):

  test.js:2: WARNING - Bad type annotation. missing opening (
   * @param {function}
                     ^

@type should have the same warning message.
